INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L031$$, 2026, $$The Littoral Combat Ship (LCS) Mine Countermeasures (MCM) Mission Package (MP) counters bottom, tethered, near surface, and surface mines in the littorals without putting Sailors in the minefield. When
 the MCM MP is embarked, LCS is capable of conducting detect-to-engage operations (hunting, sweeping, and neutralization) against shallow and deep-water sea mine threats. The MCM MP provides these
 capabilities through the use of sensors and weapons deployed from an embarked MH-60S multi-mission helicopter and unmanned offboard vehicles. MCM MP achieved Initial Operational Capability in
 31MAR2023.

 The embarked MH-60S employs the Organic Airborne Mine Countermeasures (OAMCM) systems to provide rapid and long range airborne detection and neutralization to clear operations in littoral zones,
 confined straits, choke points, and the Amphibious Operations Area (AOA) quickly. The Airborne Mine Neutralization (AMN) Module (MH-60S Helo + Airborne Mine Neutralization System) and Near Surface
 Detection (NSD) Module (MH-60S Helo + Airborne Laser Mine Detection System) achieved Initial Operational Capability (IOC) in FY 2017.

 The Unmanned Minesweeping (UMS) Module is composed of the MCM Unmanned Surface Vehicle (USV) and Minesweeping Payload Delivery System (PDS) and Towed Acoustic Generator (TAG). The
 MCM USV and Minesweeping PDS was previously known as Unmanned Influence Sweeping System (UISS) which achieved Milestone C and is currently in Full Rate Initial Production (FRIP). The Remote
 Minehunting (RMH) Module consists of a PDS and a Towed Sonar which detects and identifies bottom and tethered mines. In FY 2020, the MCM USV established a mature Technical Data Package (TDP) and
 was used for the award of the Production contract in FY2022. The Unmanned Influence Sweep System (UISS) TDP is mature and is being leveraged to procure Minesweeping PDS in Q1FY2025. In FY 2022,
 the Minehunting PDS was procured via a sole source delivery order on the Raytheon IDIQ contract. A competitive production contract was awarded for future Minehunting PDS procurements in Q1 FY2025. The
 Mine Neutralization (MN) module will consist of the MCM USV with a near-surface mine neutralization payload, necessitating future procurement of MN PDSs.

 The Buried Minehunting (BMH) Module (Knifefish Unmanned Undersea Vehicle) detects and identifies buried mines and mines in a high clutter environment. The program achieved Milestone C in FY 2019
 and entered into Low Rate Initial Production (LRIP) for five (5) Block 0 systems in FY 2019. In FY 2021, prime contractor for Knifefish is General Dynamics Mission Systems (GDMS) located in Quincy, MA,
 was awarded a contract to retrofit the LRIP systems with Block 1 capabilities and upgrade a number of performance characteristics to meet Navy bottom and buried mine hunting requirements. The Navy will
 conduct a limited validation of these capabilities during system acceptance testing and sell off to the government in Q1-Q3FY24. Upon delivery of these systems to the Navy, they were available for limited Fleet
 operations from LCS or Vessels of Opportunity (VOO). In FY25, the systems were transferred to several S&T organizations for experimentation.

 The MCM MP system procurements in this BLI are critical to deliver MCM MPs with the capability of the full detect-to-neutralize sequence and replace legacy MCM platforms.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
