INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L056$$, 2026, $$MATCALS
 Marine Air Traffic Control and Landing Systems (MATCALS) provides for continuous, all-weather, radar/non-radar approach, departure, en-route, and tower air traffic control services to an aircraft. Marine
 Air Traffic Control (ATC) provides initial, transition and sustained air traffic support for the Joint and Marine Air Ground Task Force air operations in any environment. MATCALS satisfies the operational
 requirements set forth by Specific Operational Requirements 34-22 of 12 Jul 1973; and Air Traffic Navigation Integration and Coordination System ORD 05-002 of 03 Dec 1992. MATCALS, with other Marine
 Air Command and Control Systems (MACCS) and federal agencies, provides the ability to project air combat power without regard to weather. ATC automation reduces air traffic controllers' traffic handling and
 management time, allowing more time for mission response and task accomplishment. It supports a required increase in aircraft sortie rates and contributes to extended time on target. The system provides
 for integration of ATC into the total MACCS. To provide this capability, MATCALS consists of 4 primary subsystems: (1) Air Traffic Navigation integration and Coordination system (ATNAVICS) AN/TPN-31(V);
 (2) Expeditionary Control Tower AN/TSQ-120D; (3) the Man-Portable TACAN AN/TRN-47(V)1 & 3; (4) Transportable TACAN AN/TRN-47(V)2 & 4; and various ancillary equipment. This program works with the
 Marine ATC Working Group identifying the requirements to implement the Pre-Planned Product Improvement (P3I) and evolutionary product improvements as required for the Ground/Air Task-Oriented Radar
 (G/ATOR) system, Common Aviation Command and Control System (CAC2S), ATNAVICS, Expeditionary ATC Towers, and Navigational Aids that support Marine Air Traffic Control Companies. G/ATOR is a
 multi-role, ground-based, expeditionary radar that replaces five legacy radar systems for the Marine Air Ground Task Force. It satisfies the Marine Air Command and Control System (MACCS) and the Ground
 Counter Fire / Counter Battery capabilities. Integration of ATNAVICS with the CAC2S provides a coordinated and integrated set of equipment to provide enhanced Command and Control (AC2) capability for
 the Tactical Air Command Center, Tactical Air Operations Center, and Direct Air Support Center to support aviation employment in Joint, combined, and coalition operations. Increased MATCALS component
 obsolescence of aging systems is resulting in additional Maintainability, Reliability, Improvement (MRI) costs to support the changing operational environment of the MACCS as defined by USMC Force Design
 2030 dated March 2020. Evolution of MATCALS to align with the overall USN/USMC North Star Precision Approach Landing Capability (PALC) to provide landing capability in both contested and non-contested
 environments via non-radar and radar based systems.

 NASMOD
 The Joint DoW/Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) National Airspace System (NAS) Modernization (MOD) program upgrades the DoW ATC systems at approach control facilities in concert with the FAA's
 upgrade of the National ATC System. These funds will procure ATC systems for the Navy/Marine ATC facilities. The Air Force is the DoW lead activity for the Joint Acquisition Program. The Joint Program Office
 is located at Hanscom AFB, MA.

 FLEET ATC SYSTEMS$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
