INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L062$$, 2027, $$Tactical/Mobile (TacMobile) Command, Control, Communications, Computers, and Intelligence (C4I) Systems: TacMobile is the ground station program that supports P-8A Poseidon and MQ-4C Triton pre and
 post-flight C4I requirements and Inflight Command and Control support. These ground stations provide critical reach-back capabilities between the airborne platforms and the Maritime Intelligence, Surveillance,
 and Reconnaissance (ISR) Enterprise/ decision makers. TacMobile consists of fixed-site Tactical Operations Centers (TOCs), Mobile Tactical Operations Centers (MTOCs), and Fly Away Kits (FAKs). TOCs
 are located at major Maritime Patrol and Reconnaissance Aircraft (MPRA) Continental United States (CONUS) and deployment hub sites. MTOCs are scalable, mobile versions of the TOC used for extended
 contingency operations at remote forward operating bases, while FAKs are small transportable systems that support emergent short term detachments for limited duration.

 Total program of record consists of:

 a) 6 TOCs: Systems located at Naval Air Station (NAS) Jacksonville, Florida; NAS Sigonella, Italy; Marine Corps Base Hawaii (MCBH) Kaneohe Bay, Hawaii; NAS Whidbey Island, Washington; Naval Air Facility
 (NAF) Kadena, Japan; and Isa Air Base Bahrain.

 b) 12 MTOCs: 6 systems home ported at NAS Jacksonville, Florida and 6 systems at NAS Whidbey Island, Washington.

 c) 12 FAKs: Fly Away Kits consist of a rotatable pool that is assigned to Tactical Operations Control Squadron (TOCRON) 11 in NAS Jacksonville, Florida, and to TOCRON 10 in NAS Whidbey Island,
 Washington.

 d) 1 Schoolhouse located at the Center for Naval Air Technical Training Unit (CNATT-U) NAS Jacksonville, Florida.

 The TacMobile program is comprised of 23 subsystems that utilize an evolutionary development strategy consisting of incremental upgrades synchronized to match increased P-8A capabilities while retaining
 current functionality and readiness. Incremental upgrades and tech refreshes are planned to support the Maritime Patrol and Reconnaissance Force (MPRF) Family of Systems aircraft advances.

 TacMobile Acquisition strategy is to modernize the Computers, Communications, Command, Control, and Intelligence (C4I) architecture that implements a modular system design approach allowing for rapid
 upgrades to system capabilities to keep pace with evolving operational environments. The modular design approach also allows for the fielding of incremental capability packages (CP-1, CP-2, CP-3).$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                      Date: April 2026
