INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L073$$, 2026, $$Beginning in FY 2027, the program name Digital Modular radio (DMR) has been changed to Tactical Resilient Communications (TRC).

 The Tactical Resilient Communications (TRC) system, built around the Scalable Modular Radio Cluster (SMRC), provides critical command-and-control communications for surface ships, submarines, and
 strategic shore facilities. This four-channel, software-defined radio fields NSA-mandated Cryptographic Modernization-1 (CM-1) capabilities across multiple waveforms, including MUOS, SINCGARS, and
 SATURN. As legacy systems face obsolescence and evolving cyber threats, the SMRC Multi-Band (MB) radio variant will deliver the Advanced Cryptographic Capability mandated by the NSA, ensuring secure
 and interoperable communications for joint and allied forces. SMRC MB also meets the modernization requirements to replace the Digital Modular Radio (DMR) Integrated Waveform (IW)/Mobile User Objective
 System (MUOS).

 The Tactical Resilient Communications (TRC) program also fields modernized High Frequency (HF) capabilities to provide resilient beyond-line-of-sight (BLOS) communications in contested or SATCOM-denied
 environments. The SMRC Sub and SMRC HF radio variants are key components of this system, designated by Fleet Commanders as threshold capabilities for a Distributed Maritime Environment. The SMRC
 Sub variant is essential for National Command and Control, providing survivable communications for the submarine fleet. The SMRC HF variant provides resilient, beyond-line-of-sight communications by fielding
 modernized HF LPx waveforms with a staring receiver, which is crucial for supporting the Digital HF Mesh mandated by the HF Lead Service and for joint and coalition forces operating in SATCOM-denied
 environments.

 The FY 2027 funding increase of $29.450M provides a critical investment in SMRC Sub and SMRC HF variants, directly supporting vital warfighting Digital HF Mesh (DHFM) needs. This funding increase
 will procure ten (10) SMRC Sub systems and thirty-nine (39) SMRC HF systems, with associated ancillary equipment, for installation in FY 2028, equipping submarines and surface platforms with resilient,
 beyond-line-of-sight communications. Additionally, the funding provides for the procurement and installation of SMRC Multiband Upgrade Kits to meet an urgent NSA mandate for Advanced Cryptographic
 Capability, countering evolving cyber threats. This investment closes a dangerous capability gap, ensuring our forces are equipped with the modernized, secure, and resilient communications required to maintain
 information dominance and ensure National Command and Control in future conflicts.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                      Date: April 2026
